# Understanding Classes in TypeScript

## Why Do We Need Classes?

Imagine you are building an e-commerce application.

You need to represent products:

```ts
const product1 = {
  title: "Laptop",
  price: 1500
};

const product2 = {
  title: "Phone",
  price: 800
};

const product3 = {
  title: "Monitor",
  price: 400
};
```

This works at first.

However, as the application grows, you'll need:

* Validation
* Business logic
* Methods
* Reusable structures

Managing everything with plain objects becomes difficult.

Classes help us organize data and behavior together.

---

## What Is a Class?

A class is a template for creating similar objects.

Think of a class as a blueprint.

Think of an object as a real building created from that blueprint.

```ts
class Product {
}
```

At this point, the class doesn't do anything yet.

Let's add some data.

---

## Adding Properties

Properties are variables that belong to an object.

```ts
class Product {
  title: string;
  price: number;
}
```

Now every Product should have:

* title
* price

But how do we assign values?

---

## Constructors

A constructor runs automatically when a new object is created.

```ts
class Product {
  title: string;
  price: number;

  constructor(title: string, price: number) {
    this.title = title;
    this.price = price;
  }
}
```

Creating objects:

```ts
const laptop = new Product("Laptop", 1500);
const phone = new Product("Phone", 800);
```

Result:

```txt
Product
├── title = Laptop
└── price = 1500

Product
├── title = Phone
└── price = 800
```

---

## What Does "this" Mean?

Many beginners struggle with this keyword.

Inside a class:

```ts
this.title
```

means:

> "the title property of the current object"

Example:

```ts
const laptop = new Product("Laptop", 1500);
```

Here:

```ts
this.title
```

becomes:

```ts
laptop.title
```

---

## Adding Methods

Classes can contain behavior.

```ts
class Product {
  title: string;
  price: number;

  constructor(title: string, price: number) {
    this.title = title;
    this.price = price;
  }

  displayInfo() {
    console.log(`${this.title} - $${this.price}`);
  }
}
```

Usage:

```ts
const laptop = new Product("Laptop", 1500);

laptop.displayInfo();
```

Output:

```txt
Laptop - $1500
```

