## Real Backend Example

Suppose we are building an invoice system.

```ts
class InvoiceItem {
  constructor(
    public productName: string,
    public quantity: number,
    public unitPrice: number
  ) {}

  getTotalPrice() {
    return this.quantity * this.unitPrice;
  }
}
```

Usage:

```ts
const item = new InvoiceItem(
  "Steel Beam",
  10,
  500
);

console.log(item.getTotalPrice());
```

Output:

```txt
5000
```

This is much closer to real backend applications.

---

## Common Beginner Mistakes

### Forgetting "new"

Wrong:

```ts
const product = Product("Laptop", 1000);
```

Correct:

```ts
const product = new Product("Laptop", 1000);
```

---

### Forgetting "this"

Wrong:

```ts
title = title;
```

Correct:

```ts
this.title = title;
```

---

## Summary

Classes allow us to:

* Group data together
* Add behavior through methods
* Reuse code
* Build maintainable applications

In backend development, classes are commonly used for:

* Services
* Repositories
* Entities
* Controllers
* Use Cases

Understanding classes is an important step before learning NestJS, Clean Architecture, and Design Patterns.
